A Republican strategy to counter Obama’s re-election
The leaders of the Republicans justify their policies with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth by reaffirming that the election fraud in the U.S. is less rare than the number of people killed by the lightning.
The Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures are partially undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for conducting elections in individual states.
In this sense, the majority of U.S. governments have been enacting new laws since 2009 that make it more difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has gained importance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, declare the right to register as voters on the day of the election invalid, and grant citizens the right to vote for which a court act is available.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million voters, do not have a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, in 2012, five million new voters did not have such an identity card.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to get the required ID card.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
This goes even further.
Students who are regarded as voters who are increasingly voting for democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use their photo ID issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state demanded proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to make such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws demanding that voters prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic votes.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators in eight states in 2011 endorsed laws that abolished voter registration on the day of the election.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaigns for voter registration in the 2004 general elections helped to register approximately 10 million citizens.
As a result of the measures adopted since 2009, the share of new voter registration in 2010 has decreased by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators in five other states have passed laws aimed at shortening the time for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general elections, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they make up only 13% of the state’s voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, which represented 76% of the voters, made up only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills were blocked by the veto of the democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed legislation that requires the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote.
Democratic critics denounce the political nature of the passed laws and see it as a clear goal to influence the results in the decisive states for 2012.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral body to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures are partially undermining the democratic system of the United States.
Early prostate cancer detection: should the test be done or not?
The PSA test, in fact, sometimes shows faulty results, with false negative or even false positive results, leading to unnecessary medical interventions.
This leads to greater hesitation by the already undecided men for conducting early detection tests.
Should the test be done or not?
We have seen the opinion of two specialists.
There were numerous interference factors between control groups in the U.S. studies, making it difficult to interpret these data and make clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, concluded that there is a difference in the mortality rate of patients with and without early detection.
This study also showed that with a follow-up after 12 years, the probability of metastases forming is 30 to 40% higher if no early detection was performed.
Therefore, I recommend the test from the age of 50 or 40, respectively, if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
There is also a higher risk for men of African American origin.
The most important thing is to make the right decision as soon as a cancer is detected.
There are cancers that are aggressive and others that are indolent.
The patient must be truly understood the extent of the risk of his cancer by showing him the possible options where prostate cancers can remain untreated if he does not impair the quality of life in the long run, and in these cases he is more likely to opt for active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men who have detected cancer do not have treatment because their cancer is not aggressive and does not pose a threat to their lives.
They are suggested to be actively monitored and offered treatment if the disease progresses.
With increasing accuracy, the criteria for deciding who should be treated and who should not be treated are determined.
That is why I still recommend the test.
But most importantly, talk to your doctor to determine whether it should be performed or not.
In cooperation with the International Society of Urology, Movember has developed an instrument that allows us to evaluate the advantages and disadvantages of the PSA test.
This document (currently only in English, but a translation will be available soon) can be downloaded at: http://ca.movember.com/en/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Prevention of the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle remedy to prevent cancer.
Despite progress in research, adopting a healthy lifestyle remains the best way to reduce the risk of getting ill.
It is estimated that 30% of cancers could be prevented if everyone eats well and moves adequately.
“If there were no more smokers, this value would rise to at least 50%,” said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
However, about 10% of cancers are expected to be caused by inheritance.
Several are also completely unclear.
For the Canadian cancer society, fighting tobacco addiction remains a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is responsible for 85% of cases of lung cancer.
It is also a risk factor for several other cancers.
It severely damages people’s health.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec today," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
Encouraging data: 10 years after giving up on the cigarette, the risk of dying from cancer decreases by half.
The weight
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, overweight and obesity also promote the outbreak of the disease.
They seem to increase the risk of breast, gut, mast, esophageal, pancreatic and uterine cancers.
“Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life protects against grim colon cancer,” he adds.
Nutrition
The organization also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
In excessive amounts, it increases the risk of developing a grim or mast-color cancer.
Sausage should also be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
“The latter can damage the body’s cells and lead to the development of cancer,” he explains.
Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the relationship between vitamin additives and cancer.
However, their investigations are not conclusive at present.
According to the Canadian Cancer Society, the studies on vitamin E are contradictory.
While one study found the reduction of the risk of prostate cancer, another showed an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer has not yet been clearly shown.
Furthermore, Mr. Beaulieu emphasizes the importance of talking to his doctor about his concerns and his pre-family burden.
“Taking an early detection test does not lead to cancer.”
The Higgs Boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has sparked some upset last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model - our best or " least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists, it is not entirely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely secure about it.
Let’s still assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of misleading yourself, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is inevitably an inevitable law in this world which causes that two objects cannot be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strongly as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that it also applies to such a law: the Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" consisting largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, referred to as Fermione, who obey the Pauli principle.
And on the other hand, the bosons are moving, an evil band of anarchists to whom nothing is holy - definitely not this principle, which means that they can in fact be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is absolutely amazing by the way) these bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be emphasized here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "boat" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electrical charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" at this exact location, about like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the "bearers of force" bosons.
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be frightened by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is needed – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! – to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is once again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never keep it on its own on the refrigerator.
And in the same way not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do possess a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not possess a mass.
What can all this research be "good" for now, asks Ms. Plamondon?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to carefully investigate all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who desperately hope that such deviations will be found, since the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has large shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impact
The effects of this research on the general population are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there were no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell labs did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) - has already told us that the laser was considered at first rather as a "laboratory play".
Just imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and received the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
Of course, this doesn’t mean that the activities of LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can really never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... <0x7C> Le Devoir
With her committee for "Deaths in Dignity", Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed soon, although a bill is being prepared.
However, there is still much to be done in this important topic.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had given him a two-year period.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to be helped with dinner.
Bravely, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is that my diarrhea be healed, as this is humiliating,” he said.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
“During our lives, we learn that a man is standing pishing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
“This depends on the person’s ability to take a step back,” he notes.
Because, according to several people who work in palliative care, major events take place amidst these steps backwards.
Patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Home are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overcrowded with so-called "healing" care by the doctors and nurses who take care of them.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by choking."
But because of the illness, I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I no longer have any desires in life,” she says before she accepts to put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the coming days, she expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home Victor-Gadbois you can offer a group of volunteer personal care and help with the intake of food.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, 11,700 inhabitants have a bed for palliative care.
That’s very little if you take into account that one day we’ll all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the house’s doctors.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on the desire, the dying person is given an oral care with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Yesterday night we served Mr. X a beer that died overnight.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We are helping relatives and patients alike,” says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, no day is like the other.
Besides a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows as one pushes to his honour, a 36-year-old man surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children dies in a tragic way after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to a care that is meant to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec’s health care that ensures that several physicians specializing in palliative care await with concerns the passing of a law regulating death aid and assisted suicide.
A manifesto has been in circulation since October, signed by prominent palliative care figures such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to express their contradiction to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to a high-quality palliative care before accepting to pass on to death relief.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with great pain without taking any measures to relieve her.
I’m afraid that patients want to die only because they don’t get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients despite the worst predictions to the last day.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she discontinued compelling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to discontinue the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I stopped the fight.
She told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who asked to die thank the nurse for not meeting this wish after their pain was alleviated by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, Head of Palliative Care of the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Greater Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which leads to sleeping the patient either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to sleep me,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
The realization of this report was possible thanks to a journalism scholarship from Canadian health research institutes.
