Bitcoin makes it possible to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and handling fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as so often in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, designed by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows for direct file exchange.
With 15,000 computers on the network, approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or payment method.
After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “in competition with the dollar or euro” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that can be won or purchased by gambling (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trade is controlled and processed every time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously invoice depositaries, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data associated with this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the trading bitcoins are present in the invoice book of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, which is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege to add that additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked out".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (a lot of zeroes at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for cheating very quickly twice (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task will receive 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly cut in half, probably before the end of 2012.
Bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundred millionth, which leaves a certain margin of play...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and lows.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The vulnerability used does not affect the actual protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company to pay for real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Prominent actors like Wikipedia deny donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the book of bills and showed that nearly 80% of Bitcoins are out of circulation.
In November, a “mega-closure sale” was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify an address that can be "photographed and detected" by a phone, Pierre Noizat says, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are revised in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to pass, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB intends in its report to reassess the various risks, today highly regarded, in the event that this currency succeeds.
