A constitution with the breaking bar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more than ever divided in terms of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it the unlimited authority, he has decided to put everything on a single map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly will adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had granted two additional months to this plenary for the completion of his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been relying on a preliminary text, which has been modified several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal mess.
This new initiative has only resulted in an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "the right steps down."
On the side of his supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time that forces the brothers to renounce their plan to explain to the Egyptians the text section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to recover his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging across the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly magazine Time, Mohammed Mursi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people with this resort to a hasty vote are given an ultimatum: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after adopting the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals failed to comply with the call.
Shortly before the Declaration of the Constitution in mid-November, they turned away because they believe that they have not been able to bring their views into effect.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve decision-making, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that most of the articles were adopted unanimously.
The commentators found it entertaining, by the way, that the only disagreement of the day... was expressed at the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum of the constituent assembly was not exact.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made more strict application possible.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
“Spotty” replies to the liberals who view this only as a propaganda attack.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
They have in particular in mind Article 220, which grants the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of conformity with the laws of the Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, as "the people who are asked to make an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here you can see the first signs of a theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also nurtured by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the present one.
“There is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics, who have been partly trained in the French system,” says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be ambiguity with respect to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
It refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence, Ann. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide about it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized because of the extensive powers it grants the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute is the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military’s wish, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the associations for the defence of human rights have called for.
The latter also express their concerns about the text that they regard as a threat to freedom.
The fact of blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now forbidden, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no longer any article relates to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists await holy sites, the navel of the world and a sea of sole
The Promised Land combines in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons to visit Israel.
Bow down to the holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river will receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding party, the walking on the water, the silence of the sea storm and the fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most sanctuaries are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers take the path of suffering or cross path of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts from the Roman fortress Antonia, the pretorium where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, in Christian view, is the umbilical of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the holiest place of the Jews - the Cry Wall, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave there letters with desires, which then come true.
Make a journey to the height
The ruins of the Massada Fortress form the remains of the secret hideout from enemies that Herod the Great built in 25 AD for his family.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins by their own power.
Everyone else brings an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters high is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, allegedly pagan gods lived on the mountain summit.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
On one trip, not all can be visited.
However, at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are preserved ancient Qumra handwriting or Dead Sea scrolls found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the impressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and Badeans.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guide nor souvenir shops.
Entrance is free, and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells about one of the most shaking chapters in history.
The most striking department is the monument to the children, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died sounded.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red Sea and Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinaries and oceanaries.
Astonishingly, the Red Sea bathes during winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathes there all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sole) and healing sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and to calm impaired nerves.
Touch the secrets of ancient times
These secrets hold the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous seaway that linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to traditions, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after the zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend according to all holds that touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Bookmarks for tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is preferred not in euros, but in dollars, which can be easily converted to shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you will mostly get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway train and in Haifa the only subway line in the country with six stops that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Actually, it is an underground cable car.
A ride within the city costs 6 shekels, irrespective of the means of transport, which is enough including transfers for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until Sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
On Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and food that contains both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes with sheep and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus pasta, various sauces, fried balls made from puree beans and peas (falafele), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-noutrished cats who roam the streets comfortably and unpleasantly.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the rooftops of parking cars.
Cats like lively places and don’t say no to treats.
Depending on the brand, a rental car costs from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost on average 30 shekels.
In numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists arrived in the Promised Land, equivalent to a 51% increase compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: migrants save money for language
While MPs and civil rights defenders discuss the benefits of the binding language testing law for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of families remaining at home.
On December 1, a law entered into force that requires every labor migrant to take a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this regulation applies only to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become a duty for all host workers in the future.
Not only language tests, but also tests must be placed in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be proven for both obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is official language.
This Act also exempts persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The entirety of the examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of Peoples’ Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can test in all cities; more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, civil rights activists asked the press several times before the law came into force: What does this bring about?
What changes brings the requirement to demonstrate language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, spokespersons for the Migration Authority say, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of labour migrants,” says Viktor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before departure.
Only organized recruitment will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants without work, education, language skills and medical assessment face problems.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who will put him in a dark, narrow barrack under the pretext of help, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and will work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our migrants.
"In the homeland you will be promised the One, and upon arrival you will be cheated, their passports will be taken away and will not receive the promised salary," confirms the head of the Chief Executive Office for Labour Migration of the Tajikistan Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't reproach, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the target country, but also can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford reasonable basic education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school items.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
“It’s hard without language skills,” they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Citizens' rights emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and consequently no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers remain illegal in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access prohibited for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic barriers and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
Also, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be done quickly and only for a thousand and a half.
The officials of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and this results in cases of blackmail.
“They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,” the Tajik Umed Husjkadanov told reporters.
“Do not spare the cost of false papers.”
Even on the day the law entered into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants can be counterfeit.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed using an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself the tests so paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a labor migrant three thousand rubles.
The main immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be simply purchased, both officials and civil rights defenders agree.
For the time being, the authorities can only promise to take a language course for guest workers who fall through the test for the first time.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active understanding with people is necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal weapons market
The share of legal weapons in crimes is extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten the weapons law for private weapons owners.
The authorities respond to recent events: injured in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the attack on Moscow lawyer Dmitri Vinogradov.
Police intend to ban the use of non-deadly weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal has been supported by the chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Counter-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted soon to the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, whose authors - representatives of various weapons associations - are calling on the authorities to refrain from "senseless sharpening".
The percentage of the crimes with registered weapons is very small, the criminal attorney, Vasiliy Lesnikov, told the Russian BBC.
According to the Ministry of the Interior’s statistics, 142 crimes with the use of registered weapons were committed in the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were committed for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law on private gun owners will not stop criminals from using the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, you can find any weapon in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market through several channels.
There are five such main channels, tells a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who served ten years in the Ministry of Education and the Staff.
Screenshot of a website accepting gun orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
The second channel includes illegal weapons stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the police arms chambers and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons warehouses.
In many military camps there were often explosions.
“There is evidence that in some cases it was a fire foundation to cover up the lack of weapons,” the former military official said.
According to Baranez, weapon manufacturers also make a contribution to the black market.
"Now there are countless private arms factories that do not withstand international competition and that is why they are dumping weapons on the black market, such as in Moscow," the expert said.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is its own, sometimes artisanal production, as well as a mafia that organizes smuggling,” the former military official explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated how much of each of the five channels has in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Center for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
The majority of the illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
"Half of all weapons on the black market are because of the guilt of those responsible who have to do with weapons in their work," the report said.
According to researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% from weapons theft, and 5% from illegal excavations.
A sales advisor to a weapons shop, who does not want to be named, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been purchased because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for merchants to get the supplies in an arms warehouse.
A weapon, for example a TT type gun, is purchased through a flagship.
The gun is exhibited and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the gun into the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
“The police are of course aware of everything and therefore, if they can’t comply with the plan to detect crime, they regularly carry out check purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons,” the sales advisor added.
"Like in the luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers most often find acquaintances with each other.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested coming to the station "Begowaja", where a person would be waiting for me to take me to a certain place, where we could then negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the gun there.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"In order to get a gun, I need a acquaintance who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such a acquaintance, but I don't trust him."
There are dealers in the markets, but you have to go there and date yourself with a code like "by Ivan Ivanovich, which indicates that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I’m even coming to some rings about a acquaintance I trust.
He also gives me the beat rings only because he knows I don't pick him up.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Viktor Baranez attempted to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on this topic.
According to him, the schemes have not changed.
He received a photo album in which "everything" was depicted.
