In recent days, there have been massive protests across the U.S. against low wages in Walmart branches and restaurants of popular fast food chains such as Mc Donald's, Burger King, Taco Bell, Wendy's and Kentucky Fried Chicken.
No one can yet predict whether the protests will swell further or whether they will soon go out of the air.
The protests are supported by trade unions and several left-wing non-profit organizations.
In addition to increasing the modest wages of simple Walmart and fast food employees, the protest organizers pursue the goal of establishing trade unions.
So far, this sector of the economy is hardly trade unionized.
46 cents a year?
The protests began last week after Thanksgiving, on the so-called Black Friday, which took place in the U.S. sales that attracted millions of customers, which sometimes led to handshakes.
On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, stamped out branches of the chain, whose target groups are people with low and middle income.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The goods in Walmart stores are on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
That’s why many of the low-paid Walmart employees only buy at their own workplace.
Prices and the range of goods made Walmart one of the largest companies in the United States.
According to critics, Walmart can often sell the goods so cheaply only because employees are poorly paid.
The latter also complain about harsh working conditions, such as lack of forklifts or hand scanners.
Participants in the Black Friday protests called for wage increases and expressed angry that the contribution to the owned health insurance had risen from $30 to $100 a month.
A typical Walmart employee who earns $9.5 per hour cannot afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley show that if the company increased the average wage to $12 per hour, it would cost Walmart $3.2 billion.
That’s about 1.1 percent more than they donate for wages now.
If Walmart fully transferred the wage increases to customers, each purchase would cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
For them, this would be more than $12.39 a year compared to today’s spending.
Advocates of Walmart are satisfied that protests occurred in only nine states and did not cause any losses to the company.
Black Friday lasted in its store from 8 a.m. on Thursday evening to midnight the next day, and during that period, Walmart sold about 5,000 items per second.
Walmart’s cash registers completed nearly 100 million transactions on Black Friday.
The company’s spokesman, Dan Fogelman, said in an interview on the Huffington Post website that a total of “less than five” Walmart employees deposed the work and the protest action was merely “another PR trick” by the union that organized the protests.
"Free checkout!"
The protests continued this week in New York, where their target were not Walmart stores (which were not desired in this advanced city and therefore so far non-existent) but McDonald’s and other affordable restaurants.
McDonald's says the company sells billions of servings, and yet you don't get sick days, and you won't be paid for your honest work!
Jumaane Williams, Member of the City Council of New York
Currently, the minimum wage according to federal and New York legislation is $7.25 per hour.
In fast food restaurants, the minimum wage is gradually raised, but not too strong, and on average their simple employees in New York get $8.90 per hour.
No one deserves less than it in this expensive city.
How it is possible to get so little money in New York is incomprehensible to me.
There was a time when nearly a quarter of all U.S. teenagers after school stood behind the counter at McDonald's, but the teenagers were still living with their parents.
Few saw the main source of income or planned to stay there longer.
Now, in interviews with McDonald's employees, I constantly encounter people who complain that they have to get along with this pay and sometimes even feed their children.
On the other hand, there is a comment in the Wall Street Journal forum, whose author notes that it is irresponsible to have children if you don’t know how to feed them.
Participants in the protests, which began at 6.30 a.m. Thursday in front of McDonald’s on 40th Street and Madison Avenue, demanded that the cashiers and chefs of fast food restaurants receive a minimum wage of $15 per hour, more than a double of the current minimum wage.
They continued to call for the formation of trade unions in the fast food industry.
U.S. law prohibits corporate management from stopping this goal and cautioning or dismissing trade union members.
On the other hand, business management doesn’t make it easy for them.
However, the establishment of trade unions in the fast food industry is also difficult for objective reasons.
The main reason is the high staff fluctuation.
Dissatisfied
