However, there were only a few hundred people on the spot, of which by far not all are employed in the fast food industry where tens of thousands work in New York.
It is not yet to be seen whether the spark of these protests will mobilize whole masses.
“The brain can only be moderately overlooked so far.”
The topic of extended reality, popular with fans of modern technologies, is usually perceived lately by the lens of a special glasses.
Google first presented a working model at its annual conference in summer, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had applied for a corresponding patent.
In a conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies at the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge, Shahram Izadi, it is clear that the glasses were only a transitional station for the company’s scientists.
It stimulates the ability to manipulate virtual objects in the air with bare hands and create virtual open spaces.
- Please briefly describe what research your group is conducting.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity has largely stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes also touched.
However, we want to anticipate 5-10 years and the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a progress, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much still happens on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change this, working on real three-dimensional representation systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We have to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more graspable.
For this, however, it is necessary that not only the user, but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could complement the real world much easier with virtual objects.
And first of all, we should get rid of these silly virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It’s popular, but isn’t it overrated?
- It is certainly not the universal solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because you do not always want to inform everyone around you about your actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its specific niche.
For example, in the field of object control in public places, we worked on a project where we experimented with short and narrow rather than unloading gestures.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that recorded the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but theoretically it could be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future, however, belongs to mixed control types, for example, gestures and language.
- How about that?
- We'd ask you, for example, to give me that bubble box?
They say it and point to it at the same time.
- Normally I just say it.
- Oh, that would be very difficult to see.
- Does that mean that you want the user to adapt to what a machine can and doesn't afford at any time?
- Not necessarily, but this is about mutual approach.
I think that in the coming time we will have to work mainly on the development of new sensor types that enable us to capture people’s reactions more accurately.
This can be laser sensors, for example, as they provide a good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What are your demands on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is it lacking resolution, depth or something else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
Thus, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
It is necessary to consider not only the resolution along the X and Y, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The human movements are extremely dynamic and openly speaking, the present 30 fps are too little for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed a touch sensor at our Redmond laboratory with a adjustable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds, with today’s commercial sensors closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between humans and machines.
For my work, I needed just that device, but without touch control and with more images per second.
- Shouldn't the number of cameras be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the second is a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It is not used to calculate the depth of the object.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or exacerbate the problem because more calculations would be needed.
It would be nice to have a flexible Kinect-like system where we could play with different camera inclinations to see how that helps us determine a three-dimensional position.
- If I remember right, unlike Google, Microsoft did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that with regard to the application of technology of extended reality in everyday life, the glasses have the best prospects?
- Of course, it is not pleasant to always have a smartphone in the raised hand on the go, but I think this is the best variant would be a "changing" extended reality where we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and therein lies their strength (privates can only see you), but at the same time also their weakness, because an extended reality using glasses prevents you from working with others on virtual objects.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no sensitive reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all.
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures I often speak of the fact that extended reality represents the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could definitely be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection document.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually aimed at giving the "images in the air" something hand-held, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasound rays at a certain point where the finger is located creates a feeling that is currently as weak as if someone pushed over the handballs.
There are also ribbons for the wrist that act on the nerve ends in the fingers, also this is a potential direction.
- Did you try to overlook the brain?
Does it make it feel what it should feel when it sees something?
- That's a good idea, so we haven't tried yet.
Here is another task that we will have to struggle with for a long time, namely to make a person who is physically in a closed space think he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we work on concepts with running ribbons (other than in gyms), moving platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately overlooked, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: on many topics we are only at the beginning.
