Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with Killerasteroid.
Caravanes of spaceships with inhabitants on board are heading for a replacement planet.
In order to save mankind, the important question arises, how can we reproduce in gravitylessness or on the replacement planet?
In my opinion, there are not many choices.
De facto, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Mars and Venus," says the scientist at the Sternberg Astronomical Institute, Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, on the surface of Venus there is a temperature of 500 degrees.
Life would only be possible at large heights or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The question of reproduction in space was first discussed by the researchers with regard to the flora.
Already half a century earlier, experiments with plants were conducted.
The fourth generation of peas breeded in orbit did not differ at all from the earthly species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely of tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, guards were sent into space to explore the effects of weightlessness on the development of embryos.
A normal chick is developing.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find a stop; it must be able to stand on his legs and start moving," explains the laboratory director of the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN, Vladimir Sychev.
Without a solid ground, the chicks struck wild.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborn completely diminished.
The chicks did not respond to light and sound.
Four days later, they simply died.
"Two times we let chicks slip and then set it up because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev for the failed experiment with the chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" there will be only same-sex species.
There was an experiment with rats that were already sent into space fertilized.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was just a single experiment, and the research needs to be continued," says Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats had a young offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not been solved so far.
The task is difficult.
Animals who are ripped out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive drive.
Unlike animals, man could do so in principle.
Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can produce a similar emotional background.
Such experiments are not carried out from ethical considerations.
Women have been flying into space for 50 years.
The biggest risk was Tereshkova.
The most valuable thing that humanity possesses is the female organism.
Our pigeons flew away, and no one on Earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive the space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"In the end, no one answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just a year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The child's father, Andrijan Nikolaev, was also a cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Swetlana Sawizkaja, who was twice in orbit and even performed work outside the spacecraft, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, there remains a risk.
We have very few cosmonauts who after long flights all went well and got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights in orbit," concludes Cosmonaut Walery Poljakov, hero of the Soviet Union and hero of the Russian Federation.
And yet, humanity must look for new pathways in biotechnology, radiation protection and the generation of artificial gravity.
The Hydrolaboratory in the Cosmonauts Preparation Centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here, in a floating state, the cosmonauts gain routine for working in open space.
Water represents gravitylessness.
Even though adults feel water as pleasant, it is a foreign environment; but infants feel water as a natural element.
It is as if the little Ichtyanders testify that life on land has escaped from the ocean.
There is a link between the fact that a child is in the mother’s belly for about 9 months in amniotic water, and the fact that it is then easier to get used to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to the first swimming only last 2 weeks.
“It’s too little time to forget something,” says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenova.
While for a newborn child, therefore, the loss of gravity is a much more natural condition, the woman does not go without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles retreat enormously quickly and thus also decreases the ability to press out the child.
All right, let's bypass this with birth-initiating tools.
For example, birth could also take place in a special chamber to press out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the non-significant question of Waleri Poljakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the attraction of the ground, the organism cannot train the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be placed in a stress suit in orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of elemental importance to his life.
“This experiment, which we do together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled, a completely unsuitable person,” says Igor Pestow, head of the Bioethics Commission at the Institute for Medical-Biological Problems RAN.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
But at some point it becomes reality when the Earth's inhabitants depart on their spaceships to a distant planet that will become the home for their descendants born in space.
NKÚ Chief: Black system control fails due to political fault
The Czech Republic has good supervisory bodies and adequate laws in relation to public procurement, but falls back in its application.
In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Supreme Control Office (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ), said this.
“A law is never perfect, but it needs to be applied correctly – and I think that is not the case with us,” Kala commented on the current situation.
A similar result seems to be a joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative practical example, he introduces the position of Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "black system".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls - so is the system now forbidden or allowed?
“A law must have its validity, and if something is prohibited by law, then it cannot simply come to the president of the government, and the control office, whose duty is to control compliance with the law, can hinder its activity,” Kala notes.
At the meeting of the control committee of the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint Czech-German project, which compared the laws of the two countries regarding public procurement.
What was it about in concrete terms?
This is a parallel examination that we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is a question of the European legislature setting out how public procurement is to be handled. This is what national legislation builds on. Finally, there is still the actual practical application.
We compared all this to each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we were able to notice extremely interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even a little "stronger and more perfect", but the actual application is better in Germany in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to set up new and more precise rules again and again, and we must also consider the actual application of the law.
How can the project be helpful to you? What does this project mean to you?
It is precisely such a common control that could help us to stop constantly endeavouring to perfect the laws and to lower and extinguish thresholds if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Economicality means acquiring a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of thresholds for orders does not guarantee that we will also achieve this goal.
Perhaps it’s even like that we’re only loading the system with excessive “paperwork” in this way, and those looking for gaps in the system have it much easier to exploit the system than if the thresholds remained higher.
They are talking about the problems in the practical implementation of the Czech procurement law.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there a similar authority here as our NKU, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ of the Bundesrechnungshof, which has a similar structure as we have and also has a college that is merely formed slightly differently, but in principle both authorities work similarly.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, although Germany is a federal state, that is to say that these courts of accounts also exist in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds managed by the districts and municipalities are subject to the control of the State Accounting Courts.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
However, in some respects, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly impossible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Perhaps this is because the auditors are better?
It certainly doesn’t, but as I said, I don’t particularly like comparisons like that.
In this regard, it should be noted that those countries which are an example for us are also struggling with problems.
Otherwise, you wouldn't have any cooperation with our authority, wouldn't you?
As regards Czech legislation, what importance had the amendment of the procurement law for your authority, do you already feel any effects?
Given that this novel is only in force for a short time, it has not yet affected our trials.
As our checks take place afterwards, we have to expect a certain delay here.
So far, we are more likely to experience effects in the preparation phase of future controls - so we have introduced the new control tool "Detection of risks of inefficiency" and reviewed and analyzed with this almost 14,000 public contracts - here the changes will of course have an impact, as thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, among other things.
Do you see the adoption of this law more positively, or is the system being burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "strengthened" and can no longer be complied with.
Already under the previous rules, the persons undergoing an audit are liable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational regional policy programme, the Regional Council) that any non-compliance with the procurement law is equal to a breach of budgetary discipline.
