Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports that we people like to jump to.
With our band The Tap Tap, we are more likely to make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce our readers to the project?
It is a national benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this, we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, whose end is predicted for December 21 at 11:10 in the morning.
Three concerts will be held at the same time in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00 a.m. on the day before, i.e. on 20 December.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone around 12 hours ahead of us.
Who did this idea come from?
Initially, I was sure, afterwards we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to collect enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think together with the public about the state in which we will once hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, t-shirts, bags and keychains against the end of the world, with their purchase through www.e-tap.cz, people can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world, entitled "The end of the world falls out".
Even today, the anthem is very popular on YouTube. Will it also sound on the charity concerts?
Of course, and quite at the end, provided that everything works out and the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn will be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the anthems will be broadcast live in a direct channel on Czech television.
The text of the anthem is from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with the two?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we hold many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to engage these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and enjoy it.
What is the benefit of the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible education center Studeo, where we already work for six years with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
Students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by readers who help them with different leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the readers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, we will build our own building, into which we will move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
According to what criteria did you choose them?
We wanted to build a program that appeals to all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere perform with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar “big events” planned for the future?
In May, we perform for the first time at Prague Spring, and also for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are in the US - would like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It’s not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage storage room. In addition, of course, we must carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already partly wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad, you can compare how accessibility looks in individual countries, how to deal with people with disabilities, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than we do, we were witnesses in Russia that everything is still in the east.
Moscow is absolutely not suitable for disabled people in front of Prague, where it is still unusual if someone is traveling in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even obvious that a wheelchair user is allowed, for example, in the elevator.
Fortunately, there are also clubs that are trying to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're hanging behind...
However, it should be noted that an improvement in the situation always depends on the efforts of the affected persons.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not quite usual that there a larger group of people with disabilities are actively involved in social events, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly willing personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years: What motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in engaging with something intensely.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone, I founded a music-AG with a colleague.
Well, and with time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, is usually saying, something is out of control (laughs).
But the band has only been known in recent years, or am I wrong?
It is true that working with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also started actively advertising for ourselves.
We have become aware that if you do something and you cannot see it from the outside, your own performance does not exist in a sense.
Thanks to EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was your goal to get it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be dealt with differently.
In show business today, one copies one another.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is viewed with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare to say that Tap Tap belongs to it.
The first impression that the spectator has most is of course compassion; that is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
It is people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary resources to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities succeeds, this is a progress not only for them themselves, but for the whole society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you must not make compromises in many things and also require some discipline.
But I think this is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have a rehearsal twice a week, have to complete preparatory stages and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But this is how it works everywhere, in any band that seriously works and wants to achieve something.
Currently The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them have been there since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go, you can't prevent that.
Whoever has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
