Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, making it the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space started much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were involved in space travel, but they did not always encounter understanding.
I recall here, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author introduced thoughts from his pioneering work "Entry to the Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch for "Entry to the Cosmonautics" donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and spacecraft.
In Polish magazines, he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's world-recognized contribution to the development of space was recognized, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the face-to-face side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket propulsion was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for launching or braking the draisine.
The information for this purpose comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began dealing with rocket-powered shots.
The research was conducted by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents presented show that the research has progressed to the stage of practical testing.
The research was interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting dragon from Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the press, and the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, his work was finished from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on spacecraft appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish space company (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to spacecraft.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was expected that the exploration of space would have a future.
Already in its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA endeavored to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and indeed the PTA became an ordinary member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA Chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch was on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests began in the Błędów Desert with the two-stage RM-2 missile.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a flight height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of altitude winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was stopped.
As a successor to the first RM missiles, the Meteor-1 missile was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed from this rocket, which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a transport space with a capacity of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B with a capacity of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C with a capacity of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second interkosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
