In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage of his regime for decades.
For the US government, there was no positive way out of this situation - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as it would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free the same oatmeal only worsened it.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The hostages’ fate at home provoked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo of director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the embassy was occupied, six ambassadors managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian Ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to conceal their true identity - they traveled disguised with Canadian passports as members of a film staff allegedly visiting the scenes in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of Genres
The plan developed by the "exfiltration" expert, Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood's collaboration.
To make the covering credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck Film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels change in the film - on the one hand the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and there are no great differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which come from ironic and slightly overwhelmed.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, in the office halls, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has succeeded in a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after Crime No Child Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film not playing in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed this director’s previous films from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also proves this sense in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place – the entry sequence of the ambassador’s insurgency is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveys the sense of confusion and unpredictability that happens when the story moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck with his team even in fictional scenes (the false film rod on a basar in Tehran).
Too much plot in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the filmic sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping reality somewhat - which then doesn't always look so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is avoided by a phone call in America, or even the persecution on the runway, look somewhat artistic).
The weakness of Argo is its too broad scattering, due to the need to have to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, so they are far from alone in the film.
As a result, Affleck’s film loses some of its tensile power. It is a film that can be followed with some interest and enjoy the design and the retro style that reminds us of a 70th-year-old thriller.
However, he awakens enthusiasm hard.
However, it is sufficient as a memory of a piece of history that is still alive in some ways, and as a proof of how overwhelming the ideas of the all-powerful and all-knowing intelligence services are.
