Szabo: "Germans have to play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the inclusion of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations, Berlin balances this at a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week Germany initially signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians at the United Nations.
Then Berlin abstained.
- Why? - Yeah.
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence – without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from the vote when it came to establishing a flight ban zone.
This was ultimately enforced by NATO.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is just shifting its foreign policy away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, to a German foreign policy.
It makes it more difficult for Europeans not to have a coherent and unified policy.
Thus, the Germans are reflected between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching on their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy as they have France or the UK.
What does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It also shows the willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance in the Middle East conflict and voting in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to hit the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That definitely plays a role.
But I wouldn’t like to put too much weight on it either, that’s not a totally unilateral relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I believe that there is a great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the United States.
That is why I don’t think this was such a dramatic breakup as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect with this.
Because it signals that it is to be taken seriously as an international player and his interests to be taken into consideration.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly voted for a veto.
Are there disagreements between the United States and many European nations?
Due to American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the administration under Obama secretly has quite a lot of understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government of course cannot publicly represent this position.
I think the actual differences are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so excited about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
This is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive topic.
But I believe that the Germans are clear that they have to play a more independent role.
Sees Germany itself in the role of an important international player - does Germany want to take a leading role at all?
Or is Germany still having a heavy leadership role?
Germany is not yet accustomed to it, this is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, there are different anti-German feelings free every time Germany takes on a larger role.
That doesn’t make it easy for the Germans.
That’s actually the old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must be receptive to a variety of neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is continually decreasing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else will stay there?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's uncomfortable for them and makes them much more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly investigate the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
