Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Felt lice and scabies are among the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main stakeholder groups?
Syphilis and trippers occur mostly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five syphilis cases reported in Germany will be transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonades, candidiasis (mushroom), trippers and human papillomaviruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV among heterosexual adults here is relatively low – nevertheless: about 20 percent of new HIV infections account for this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur significantly more frequently than in other populations.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, human papillomaviruses are also common in adolescents.
How has the number of infections developed?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are reportable.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has more than doubled from 1,697 diseases in 2001 to 3,698 diseases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has declined since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the year before.
What symptoms indicate a sexual illness?
The infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort during urination, discharge, lower abdominal pain as well as blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause pain or other symptoms and therefore remain unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
Because in part, pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be passed through lubricating infections and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations especially for frequently changing sex partners.
Early diagnosed most STIs can be cured and late consequences can be avoided.
