When the darkness comes over the country in Norway and the weather gets colder, Norwegians stream to a festival here in Fagernes, which is dedicated to this, well, really very bribery specialty.
"You eat it raw and then rinse it down with a glass of Aquavit," says Havard Halvarsen, who actually works at the local fire station but also hosts the festival as a so-called "Rakfisk general".
People around us eat small fish cubes and eat large amounts of alcohol.
"Many people like the Aquavit more than the Rakfisk," says Havard.
The spirit can disrupt the smell.
I've tried a few cupcakes.
If you avoid getting the Rakfisk close to your nose, it’s not bad – like sushi, which has a pretty long bus ride behind it.
Rakfisk is the product of a very different, much poorer Norwegian era, when there were no cooling facilities yet and fish was immersed in airtight salt water barrels in the autumn.
In the deepest winter, it was then removed after long fermentation and eaten - undoubtedly using alcohol-depressed senses.
Even a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Today the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by a thriving labour market, high wages and comprehensive healthcare.
Even from Sweden, the old rival, who was far richer than Norway not so long ago, immigrants flow.
Rakfisk is seen as something important - an essential, but strictly smelling part of Norwegian history.
It is one of the most expensive dishes you can buy here.
But in fact, here everything is expensive - a small glass of beer or a sandwich costs proudly 10 euros.
Norway doesn’t often get into the world press, and most people don’t seem to bother that.
Here you still hate to call Anders Breivik by name - that racist right-wing extremist who shot 77 men, women and children last year.
Instead, it only refers to the "incident of July 22."
Norwegians are hard to accept that someone in their peace-loving country is capable of such brutal murders.
Since the early 1970s, the growth of Norway has been one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, who distributes the round tray with mature Rakfisk and embodies the Nordic ideal with her long blonde hair and stinging blue eyes.
We are, as they say, a prudent people.
Your English is perfect, just like most people here.
We're not very enthusiastic, we don't like boasting.
Norway has handled its oil wealth very carefully – a large part of the industry’s revenue is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When in the years until the world economic crisis everyone threw money that they did not have at all, Norway kept its wallet firmly closed.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"And of course eat Rakfisk," she adds with a laugh.
I stand in the snow and stand for another dish - from Rakfisk I have enough.
Such an elk burger is definitely something else.
But in the evening the stinking fish is again on the dining schedule.
The hotel I stay in is one of several venues that organize a Rakfisk dinner where guests can vote for the best - or perhaps the most challenging - fish.
There is a live TV circuit to a fly-clotted showmaster surrounded by plates with Rakfisk.
The show is similar to the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What score do you have in the mountains for the best fish, Thor-Jürgen?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
You clap and laugh.
A man falls from his chair, possibly overwhelmed by the aquavit.
But perhaps it is the strict humidity of the whole fish.
Mexico’s Enrique Pena Nieto faces difficult start
While Mexico’s future President Enrique Pena Nieto is preparing for his office, Will Grant from the BBC analyzes the challenges that are coming to him and the mixed feelings of his people.
Currently, traffic in Mexico City is particularly poor.
Even on better days, this is a constantly clogged city, but on Monday, a steel ring was built that closes several important traffic routes to the capital and causes chaos on the roads.
The goal, however, was not to disrupt travellers on their way to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president Enrique Pena Nieto will receive the presidential bond and take over the leadership of the nation.
He is facing a complex task.
Under the departing government of Felipe Calderon, Mexico has proven itself economically well, but the country is facing a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My government is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy to achieve this goal.
Before joining the U.S. President, Pena Nieto served as governor of his home state, Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, the opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
For example, in the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, people like to remember him.
The residents of the resort attribute him the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can drive on one of the highways that Pena Nieto had built and which represent a great improvement compared to the fragile, hollow roads that once existed here.
Plaques with its name also hang outside of a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
“We expect real and ongoing change from him,” said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the Pena Nietos party, which is the PRI.
In particular, with regard to security and the economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party puts great expectations on Enrique Pena Nieto.
The opposition’s allegations, the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has big plans for the country.
He is an excellent statesman, but above all he is also someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state not many people share this view of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway crossings and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are decisively urban in nature.
Earlier this year, the military was activated to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a particularly acute problem.
On a spot of Brachland near a large landfill, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the last two years alone.
During the term of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that even surpasses that of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for their violence and the murders of innocent women.
Critics Pena Nietos believe that he has at least not addressed the problem of women’s murders during his term of office.
In the worst case, however, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building, typical of the fallen neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
But her family believes she was murdered by her companion.
“When I arrived at her home, it seemed like her body was washed,” recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she was beaten, and the body was already in place.
While her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall, beside a cross that carries a single word: justice.
But this one, as the family says, has been denied so far.
The authorities have treated me as if I was a talker, a agitator, a neighbor.
They just want to accept their judgment and keep their mouths silent.
"But that's not possible if there were so many form errors and failures," she says.
If President Pena Nieto receives the presidential binding on Saturday, he also takes on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have been affected by violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has promised to take particular care of this issue during his term.
“I hope that as president he is the way he was as governor,” says PRI Congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
The victims’ families in Ciudad Neza are most afraid of this.
Prosecutor says Bradley Manning didn't complain about ill-treatment
Attorney’s Office opposes Bradley Manning’s accusations of being abused in prison
The hearing deals with Manning's time in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defense aims to reject the charge due to harsh conditions of detention
U.S. Army Freedman Accused of Stealing Thousands of Confidential Documents
The prosecutor's office on Friday tried to find that army-free Bradley Manning - charged with the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - missed several occasions to complain about his alleged mishandling in military detention.
During a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein stated that documents of weekly visits made by Manning's prison officials during his nine-month imprisonment in Quantico, Virginia did not contain any complaints about his treatment.
A day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a defense request to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh imprisonment - Manning had testified that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. Army’s intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had seated under reinforced detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officials asked Manning questions and wrote his answers.
When Fine surveyed him on Friday about the forms, Manning admitted that he had judged treatment by his guards as "excellent" and treatment by the facility as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, according to Fein, contained no complaints of abuse, although the officials had interviewed Manning directly for his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and told him to deal with them, but they were not logged.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems', and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicide thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observational status for "injury prevention".
The military said it assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the risk of suicide - to his own and the protection of others.
“I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well, and to get rid of the observational status for injury prevention ... to be able to achieve a higher quality of life in my view,” Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday he was arrested and relocated to Kuwait, where he was detained nearly two months before being relocated to the Quantico Marine Base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide in Kuwait and once became unconscious due to the heat.
Not to know what was going on with him or in the outside world has been a burden.
“My world shrinked on Camp Arafjon, on that cage,” Manning said Thursday.
I thought I'd die in that cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell — at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours — and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or just lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that entered his cell from the outside.
If he turned around at night and guards couldn’t see his face, he was awakened to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning’s lawyer formally appealed against Manning’s treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, Judge Manning also asked about an accusation he had raised in his statement Thursday - so he slept naked one night in his cell in Quantico and had to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at a morning count.
Manning had testified that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
At the interview on Friday, Manning said he had closed by order of his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with, but he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, trying to show an official that he did not pose a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the bundle of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and drastically reduce his degree of detention if he is convicted in his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for early next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will plead guilty to lesser offences, while other charges that are considered too extreme are to be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend and the prosecutor’s office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all inmates detained under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the favoring of the enemy, the unlawful publication of intelligence information on the Internet, the transfer of national defense information, and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty in all charges, he is threatened with life imprisonment.
The Mexican-American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame emigrants - they remember hard times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at the passport control when remorse became wide within me.
Signs referred to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicans"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Foreigners").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure of which to go.
I grew up in Central California and was called a Mexican for my whole life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Ire" or my friends in New York "Italy".
Later, I decided to be “Mexican American”.
But this was Mexico.
And in my grandfather's home there was no need for shortcuts or bindings.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to stand in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I won’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in the line for foreigners.
I thought about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
The agenda included all the topics expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason Mexicans are now equally likely to stay in Mexico rather than emigrate to the United States.
He wants to ally with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade block in the model of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue Mexico’s war on drug cartels, even though he did not give details about it.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans presumably never waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country’s leadership under a shotgun to leave more than half of their territory to them.
But for Mexicans thinking in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official has even the mildest criticism of Mexico, you can hear complaints - in the Mexican press and among the elites of the country - about how the Americans oppress the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the Montezumas children are on the war path.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Would you like to talk about resentment?
There's more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers, people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican origin live in cities such as Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio is that at one point in our family tree a person — perhaps a parent or grandparent — did not have a chance to emigrate to Mexico and to the north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, untrained, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness applies to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may now have lived the American dream, attended good schools, and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of it as the American dream we are living, not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership class don’t like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our bands to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they wouldn’t have gone.
And then we wouldn’t see ourselves trapped behind the silk curtain now—with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans take this to them.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel neither belong to the one nor to the other country.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico, we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as a Mexican.
As I should learn during my journey, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational bourgeoisie want to resume their connections to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
Well, well.
That's not going to happen.
Too many injured feelings.
And given the unjust distribution of income, unrestrained corruption and drug violence, many of us are not sure if it is really a great country.
I'm afraid you'll have to go through it alone, Amigos.
That's fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet willing to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans are resentful of how their family members were treated just not so long ago.
Hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar for peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the germ.
Amid the usual accusations, countless buildings have been destroyed, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed – and for the first time rockets have been hit from Gaza near the Israeli metropolis Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
Although Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historical conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not – Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this mess.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly patt situation could finally end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism does not seem appropriate in the light of the current situation.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 continues, the fighting this week has strengthened the hard-fighted on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has controlled the Gaza Strip since 2007, are claiming to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its group itself suffered great losses.
Although several Hamas leaders have been killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip have been pierced in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has so far failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, which is controlled by the rival, moderate Palestinian group Fatah.
And the Hamas leaders could conclude that they have time on their side.
Just as Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends on their side.
Turkey, a renewing, regional power once considered to be Israel’s closest Muslim ally, has taken up the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Rejoicing Hamas supporters believe that Israel is forming an Islamist half-moon – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, over Syria, where rebels of an increasingly Islamist embossment might stand before the overthrow of Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies threaten the king.
And in particular the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Mursi in Egypt – by far the most inhabiting and most important Arab country – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the region’s balance sustainably.
Hosni Mubarak, the secularist despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the brotherhood with Hamas is married and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that even Israel and the United States cannot push out.
Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer a danger.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has proven itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep quieter.
In diplomatic terms, the United States remains unwaveringly attached to its position. Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free of suicide bombers – not least thanks to the blockade systems that enter the West Bank and thus the main part of any Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements that have been declared contrary to international law.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has partnered with an even more militant group in the run-up to the elections on January 22 under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these deceitful Palestinians beat them and leave them their own state?
If they really had control over the West Bank, wouldn’t they just like their fellow fighters in the Gaza Strip fire rockets?
No, it’s better to keep them behind the wall and punish them if they dare lift their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to stand up, but the Arab Spring could make them a tick through the bill.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense state is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments repair their economy.
The fact that pragmatic President Mursi worked together with Barack Obama to reach a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think more long-term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking scary steps towards democratization, Palestinians will continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a bowl of powder that will undoubtedly one day explode in Israeli-occupied areas, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The oppression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only exacerbate.
Bloody missions to push Hamas back in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need a push from the outside
The right answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel resigns for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give foreigners more influence in enforcing this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, stop arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Foreign Arab nations should also encourage Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama must also contribute to encouraging Israel to negotiations.
During his first term, he failed to present his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems as if he was equally inclined to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a major interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first laws on uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have come into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive-green lids, which are also printed with drastic pictures that show sick body parts and infants and children ill from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small fonts, will be on Saturday.
In this way, Australia is introducing the world’s strictest regulations on tobacco packaging.
The Australian federal government wants to stop young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous picture of tobacco use.
The government is based on studies that have shown that people who have not started smoking at age 26 will not start smoking at a 99% likelihood.
“You can see from young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, quoting studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a slight impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favor the black market trade, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger quantities of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette cases and silicone lids to cover unbearable packaging has increased enormously since the British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco have challenged the law two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units in wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good deal.
According to experts, the popularity of social media is among the population to which the plan is aimed.
A number of Australian laws have banished tobacco companies from television advertising, prohibited them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most traders to no longer interpret cigarettes in stores. Now tobacco advertising has switched to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote their products don’t get around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a health researcher at Sydney University.
On social media like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook, Freeman has seen a rise in reviews of brands written by “very normal people.”
One has to ask oneself: Is this just a private person who finds such a favor of Marlboro cigarettes that they even make a video for it - or is it a marketing agency that has to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that rather than marketing, the industry focuses on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries are conducting major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has had talks with other countries considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to prescribe photographic warnings in 2001.
Meanwhile, these have been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures don't affect me.
I just ignore her.
“You just take a pinch and put the box away,” says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box that prints a photo with a mouth tumor.
Honestly, there's only one reason I'd stop, and that's my little girl.
James Yu, the operator of the tobacco shop “King of the Pack” in downtown Sydney, says uniform packaging made it difficult to replenish his shelves.
“I used to take an hour to sort a delivery, now I need four,” Yu says.
"The government should have completely banned cigarettes - then we would have said okay, that's it, we're closing," he added.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored.
This Thanksgiving I spent unexpectedly five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to make a few thoughts about boring.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting half a day at the airport for a flight is quite annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts suggest boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it is for us - and our children - okay to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to lose itself in interesting thinking processes, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us nowadays almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
Should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
I will come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn't think so.
“Truly, boredom has a very long story,” he says.
The house walls of Pompeii decorate a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and presenting the idea before a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues concluded that boredom is the experience of wanting to perform a satisfactory activity but cannot be defined.
Boredom is therefore different from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, on the other hand, there is no desire to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, exists in a "disruption of the attention process, paired with a bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing."
Boring can sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two conditions may be related, bored people see the problem in their surroundings or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we are bored, even when we just have trouble focusing.
In their study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person reads a magazine.
Some groups listened to a loud television show from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content; others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly noticeable, while the third group did not hear these noises at all.
The people who listened to the hardly hearable television said they felt more boring than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find any reason for it, and attributed their difficulties to the boring.
Trying to focus on a difficult or exhausting task can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when one performs a single-tone activity - "like searching for defective products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not feel bored."
Indeed, he says, we now know that scratching and scratching, often interpreted as signs of boredom, can even fight them by keeping people more physically attentive.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point - my late flight, a loud loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
Some people get bored easier than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a "scale of boredom susceptibility" in the 1980s.
On the scale, statements like “Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything.”
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are getting bored more often than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – especially in terms of the need for more and a wider variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a fairly tense pile.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents with a pager seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of teenagers were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% said they were bored when they were not at school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know if the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is sure that "youth is felt particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers do not have a great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my original question: Is boring healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are investigating the relationship between boredom and creativity, which is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
“With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
When one is bored and you use this energy to play and cook guitar, you’re happy.
However, while television can create feelings of happiness in the short term, they are fleeing again in the long term.
So if you give your bored child an iPad, you can get it away from the boredom, but it hasn’t learned to entertain or control yourself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, "Self-control is transferred from one situation to another."
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we see them too critically.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from the constant activity and technology intrusion.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we need to be bored more often, but boring is the persistent desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth, people are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
“In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it’s hard to get busy when the noise is quiet.”
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law.
19-year-old community college student and soccer player Anthony Orozco stands for a crime in southeastern Colorado that will soon be legal in this state: the possession of a few few marijuana slices and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils - cavalry offences, each with a $100 fine - and received a court appointment.
“We are treated like criminals,” Orozco said.
But is he one too?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for its own use, the response for hundreds of smaller drug offences depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of wrongdoing around marijuana are already dropped here and in the state of Washington, which has approved similar measures.
Police authorities no longer persecute adults over 21 years of age for possession to a small extent, which will be permitted by law as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative districts of Colorado have announced that they will continue tracking existing marijuana crimes and still quote people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denvers to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana businesses from opening in their communities.
“This situation is evolving so quickly that I don’t even know what will happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
And regulators in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance on the establishment of a licensing system for the production, production, distribution and sale of the drug - and have a deadline in mind until 1 December 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado is in any case ahead of most states in terms of regulation of marijuana, where the drug was first legalized for medical purposes and then for self-consumption.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited for guidance,” says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Supervisory Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent to follow,” he adds.
The Washington Law, called I-502, enters into force on 6 December and thus also forms the endpoint of a gray zone where the state licensing system does not yet exist, but possession is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time – such as how to agree on the state’s requirement of “adequate access” to licensed marijuana with the prohibition of cannabis shops within 300 meters around schools, parks, playgrounds and childcare facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the Seattle metropolitan area,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his employees in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana crimes in persons over the age of 21, and that the police would "from now on" not seek criminal charges for these crimes.
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce urban regulations to regulate medical marijuana growers and that drug traffickers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his authority would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to encourage consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people must be held responsible for possessing about 50 grams or less of marijuana in court, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
“Our authority has a duty to prosecute violations that were crimes at the time of the crime,” Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are dubious even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the biggest city in the district, no longer display adults for possession of smaller quantities.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to abandon all pending ownership proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to agree on personal marijuana consumption with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions throughout the state unveiled a profound division among local officials with regard to the great green experiment.
District attorneys are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents defendants in court for marijuana offences and acts as spokespersons for the national marijuana reform organization.
“They have spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for not yet accepting legalization,” he said.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana such as alcohol, Colorado and Washington are acting as national pattern cases for the legalization of drugs.
While advocates and state officials are preparing for an age of legal sales, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at federal level as a criminal offence.
Advocates of the legalization movement hope the Justice Ministry will surrender.
Despite several eye-catching arrests by medical marijuana consumers and sellers, the federal government has allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy advisor to the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officials are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of drugs, they are likely to refuse to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana businesses under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for the federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipalities approved moratoriums for new marijuana businesses, although they could only open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a town in the west, decided a six-month ban that is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
Our community has voted against this amendment.
We determine what the community has chosen, not what the state has chosen.
Many questions remain open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once thought was the largest stamp of knowledge in the world, a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization - free thinking and tolerance.
But within two weeks of my entry to Worscester College at the end of the 1980s - where I had planned to study history - I had packed my suitcases again and thus brought about the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed in tears.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard said I had gone because I had a problem with comrades having sex in the neighboring room.
The author A N Wilson declared that I had left university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
The truth was less amusing.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran because I suffered systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my rather unusual name, or because I had come from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason - one reason that seemed so narrow and cruel in this alleged cradle of enlightenment: my now-deceased father Woodrow Wyatt had been an important advisor to Margaret Thatcher and I was an advocate of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Now, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate rights students is suffering similar persecution.
The organized and rising hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same protection of equality that benefits gay, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Common Room (JCR) of Corpus Christi College say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked, and unwanted because of their political views."
They demand a place in their college’s equal rights committee to ensure that their opinions can be expressed freely.
Their situation was worsened by a recently broadcast documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right," which portrayed Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazis.
It was shown, among other things, by graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Oxford, who drove in a Rolls-Royce and protected with silver-colored suit and silver-colored walking stick.
At other universities, conservative students say they are regarded as “sin-goats for the introduction of higher tuition fees.”
20-year-old Luke Black, Vice President of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without having met us at all.”
Samuel Roberts, 21 and history student at Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, believes such a climate is "unpleasant". 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, president of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has seen a growing rejection of JCR members to moderate right students.
“This poses a threat to the intellectual discourse and the well-being of the members,” she says.
In my first weeks in Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university had voted in favor of not awarding Margaret Thatcher - a former student - an honorary degree due to cuts in higher education.
The atmosphere would have even scared Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students and the tutors got to know each other, I got a taste of what happened to come.
I experienced that the tutors not only tolerated the mockery of Tory students, but even participated with pleasure.
Political issues such as the miners’ strike, the privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against the apartheid regime in South Africa have found their way into the wood-paved rooms of the tutorium.
At my first of these events, I was meant to translate French texts from the 18th century into English, and I had not been prepared for what would come.
“Ms. Wyatt,” tutor Harry Pitt (now deceased) said, “please translate the first paragraph.”
I stumbled on it.
Pitt was a little man with a face like cake dough, and quite reckless.
"Are Thatcher's supporters refusing to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students kicked.
In my eyes there were tears.
"I suggest that you take a few French lessons in your free time - so if you are not too busy with your social activities," Pitt whispered to me.
I went back to my room with my head hanging.
That evening, I was sitting alone in college for dinner when someone tapped me on my shoulder.
It was a second-year English student named James who presented himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is the way it is.
Anyone who is suspected of being a Tory is being harassed.
It's bad enough for me, but they know your father's close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be worse for you.
Most Tory-first-semesters pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
At a local pub I later tried to change myself.
I insisted that I didn’t agree on all points with Mrs. Thatcher.
This trick should prove to be unsuccessful.
Ironically, a graduate in philosophy, politics and business, who had attended the conservative Eton College, said to me, "You're the daughter of a fascist pig."
You're polluted.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverse and dirty.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked me.
They hit each other, don't they?
I felt like homosexuals had to feel before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after darkness?
Should I have to turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years before me stretched in front of my spiritual eye to a purgatory of restraint and isolation.
The only tutor to openly disclose himself as a Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history, who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising Thatcher on foreign policy and writing speeches for her.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-scale, and rejected it for his Marxist-deterministic history perspective.
In 1997 he took a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I started hanging between Oxford and my parents’ house and found shelter with more open friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said.
They would never do this, not in my city of dreaming tower tips.
Even my Communist friends always showed up perfect manner.
His wet eyes were clouded.
Give it a chance.
I'm sure they're just kicking you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance was weakened.
One of my male friends, also a Tory adherent, had ceded to the pressure and abandoned his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, when another history teacher seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Although I was secretly ashamed, I admitted that my parents had undergone "brainwashing" and called them "old fool."
The relief only lasted for a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch Press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my cubs gave up.
As they left, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
I'd like you to call me a whirlwind tail.
But no 18-year-old should ever suffer such intimidation and wickedness in an educational institution.
And even more tragic, it was Oxford - a university that not only brought about 14 Tory Prime Ministers, but hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought to this day.
