The most difficult profession in the world: the human working animals of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the Indonesian volcano carriers put their lives and health at risk by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur across the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 mine workers who earn their lives by picking up sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, he must go down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur-containing gas flowing from the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders along the desired stone paths.
While it is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2386 meters, the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb in turtle speed, keeping their balance and taking their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened by a French tourist who crashed on the slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen’s mining workers earn 5 Eurocents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine.
Arriving upstairs, they bow the path between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 exploits the occurrences of the volcano and (never better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for every kilogram of sulfur.
They then sell this for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) each to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of matching woods, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Because we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally makes three routes a day.
For each track it takes three hours, after which it has completed, but at the end of the day it then has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) combined.
What looks like a miserable wage for such an inhumane effort is, however, three times what he would earn from field work.
“The daily wage of mine workers here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day during the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high,” explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto with his family returned to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and that is for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I brought them to Islam to Java."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life at risk for Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left his first traces at him, despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
“I’m going to work here for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French,” he promises in a more than just acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but life-punished young man could work as a tourist guide, waiter or hotel reception, but instead he does the work of a carry-on.
He divides a dirty wooden hut with other carriers and stands up every morning at two o’clock because the sulfur also flows out at night, where his characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small headlamp on his helmet, which he bought from his own money.
Approximately 400 carriers load the baskets with sulfur on their shoulders at the crater bottom.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur mining to save costs, and does not supply any equipment to carriers who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) surcharge per camera, which the guards of this nature park demand along with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human carrier.
“This work is for animals and not for humans,” protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old stem carrier who has been working for three decades since leaving school at Kawah Ijen.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as he can" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulphur burns the throat and itching the eyes, when the wind suddenly turns and the miners cling in the thick columns that rise from the crater, the men are so hard that no one complains about serious illnesses ... of course, except for the usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, pain in the knees and bladders on the shoulders that weigh from the crater.
With the basket on his back, Unainik at the age of 53 is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, transported by three trucks on a goat trail between the bushes to the camp in Tamansari at a distance of 18 kilometers.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, in which some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the elder at the age of 30 also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty lasts generation after generation in one of the toughest professions in the world: those who work as human burdens at Kawah Ijen.
Singapore needs babies to save the economy
The Singaporeans blame for having no children on their careers, the stress and the cost of real estate and children’s education.
“The population of Singapore needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife: let us fulfill our citizenship duty and create life!
It seems unbelievable that the verses are part of a mint candy advertising, but nevertheless – or precisely because of it – they became a viral video on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
The sentences are part of a rapper song, the local proverbs such as "slide a "bao" into the furnace to make fun of the low birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising company BBH, who shot the video, maintains the hope that the advertising will reach in a fun way to draw attention to the problem.
Her creative director Douglas Hamilton says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill their “national duty.”
This is just for the internet, so we had to make it funny and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
When reproducing, we are the worst in the world, so we realized that it was a topic we had to take care of.
We knew the government had tried a lot, such as marketing perfume with pheromons or organizing speed dating evenings (fast flirts).
Possibly many of these ideas were creative, but they did not necessarily lead to success.
So we thought, why don’t we do something as creative as we can to address this problem, like composing a rap?
1.2 Children
The one who doesn’t take this issue easily is the Singapore government.
Every year, she spends $1,300 on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for couples and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But everything has had little success so far.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its rulers and its strict social controls.
According to its national population authority, the birth rate is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time this rate was above 2 - also known as replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have any more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Authority, says this is due to "better education" and "bigger career opportunities".
“This has enabled people to marry and form a family to have significantly more choices in terms of life goals and set priorities,” she explains.
These social changes have contributed to the higher number of singles and the delay of marriage and births, which results in a reduction in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at a dramatic increase in immigration to counter the decrease in population led to resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where barely hidden xenophobia flourishes against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons that the ruling party in Singapore achieved its worst election result since independence last year.
Since the elections, an attempt has been made to correct the problem with higher contributions and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has the known impact on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare costs and immigration policies, the example of Singapore also shows unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to ensure that not so many small houses are built.
