UNASUR Summit concluded without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the heads of state and government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially informed that they would hand it over after the closure, but then stated that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian government.
For questions about the text, they stated that the content was presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, in brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was restricted at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received from the press spokespersons of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document spread during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more information.
The presidential office of Peru then sent to the media an e-mail containing the "closing statement" of the summit, but it was the declaration of Humala and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit South America-Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite a strong press call, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities emphasized that information systems were available for journalists, but they limited access to information to a great extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of the Hague that resolves a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago to hear the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are presenting to this international court," Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and continues to be a country that complies with international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, reaches agreements and submits to international courts,” Piñera said.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 following the dismissal of its president Fernando Lugo, has not participated in the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, saying that 16 decisions have been made and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total investment of $17 billion have been set.
On the decisions taken, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, to which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be advanced to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and against organized cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to low-price drugs and the internet in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the case of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant trains, but rather serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future,” Humala added.
“We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas ... and thus unify our countries and open up new economic forms,” the Peruvian president said in a read statement.
Among these projects, there are five Peruvian projects on the cross-axis of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although it did not provide any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its re-establishment in the Union of South American nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighborhood relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In that sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that he was expecting a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgment of the International Court questioned by Bogotá.
“I may meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow,” Santos said.
"We will review all these paths - they are not excluding, and the agreement with Nicaragua also makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the assumption of the country’s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the action plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru has the presidency on the time of the regional block.
