Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the result of the study: HIV-positive.
"It was as if a bomb struck," he says about the moment when he received the diagnosis, which the doctor "tried to weaken" without any recognizable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such a commitment that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), to which he came after several battles in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options, and more stigmas.
At the time, the director of a clinic at IMSS himself avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to a blind alley."
At the time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who don’t know about their illness and in whom the virus has already caused damage and exhausted their immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who begins treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly equal," said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG's HIV unit, saying that this information was published in April of this year by a prestigious scientific publication.
The specialist in infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008 the scientists have concluded that while AIDS is not a death sentence, that 500 years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the immune system of individuals at the beginning of treatment, and that those who are not drug-dependent are more likely to have a CD of up to 50 years.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those who are diagnosed with HIV positive at the age of 25, in this sense, "can easily be 75 years old as long as they are under control," said the expert.
In order to properly classify this progress, it must be remembered that Mexicans’ life expectancy is now an average of 76 years.
Even though mortality has declined significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has declined from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS Annual Report), it is nevertheless correct that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of patients have died in the national database.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year, there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that since 2005 there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs.
- So why are people still dying from it?
In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years, we have not had any medication supply problems. The problem is that people are in a far-advanced state because they do not know their infectious state, that is, in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. To be able to influence global mortality, early diagnosis is required, which is why massive detection tests need to be offered to anyone who needs to do so."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco) and also the patients like Fabrizio, who had conducted his test in a private laboratory, even for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who had already been in the AIDS-Phase (despite his young age).
Everything is different if you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to hear anything.
“If I have to die, I’d rather burst three times,” they say in my case.
The change was for improvement, I feed well, exercise and take the medications.
Nowadays, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," Fabrizio said, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today as part of the World AIDS Day.
The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like everyone else.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms Behind the Store Table
There are large holes between the health programs and the simple citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken on the case of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
“The distribution of condoms was actually increased in places where they were previously delivered individually, now they are giving us packages of a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom,” he said.
Among the people at risk for new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you need it?" is a common mockery question from social workers, counselling staff in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the healthcare system who don't want to expose young people, the correspondent said.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be located not only behind the shop table, but in output devices in public toilets of facilities frequently visited by young people.
It is not to promote promiscuity.
They should not be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question whether preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
“Sexuality doesn’t look like that; it’s best to bring condoms closer to those who already have sexual activity,” he pointed out.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 accumulated cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
Nationally, the state ranks fourth in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and thirteenth in HIV.
92% of infections occur through sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people in each registered case who don’t know about it.
